    "recap_url": "https://www.SMCGaels.com/news/2026/3/21/baseball-bsb-gaels-set-for-rubber-match-on-sunday-after-9-5-defeat-to-waves",
    "recap_headline": "Saint Mary's College of California",
    "recap_text": "MORAGA, Calif.\n- The Saint Mary's baseball team dropped game two of its conference opening series with Pepperdine, 9-5 Saturday evening. Both starters would get no-decisions in quality outings, but the Waves offense tacked on seven runs over their final three at-bats to seal the four-run victory.\nMulti-hit performances for the Gaels came from\nMakoa Sniffen\n,\nDario Freschi\nand\nCody Kashimoto\n. Kashimoto's two-hit game pushed his hit streak to a season high 15 games, while Sniffen doubled twice to raise his season total to seven, good for second most on the team.\nTanner Griffith\nhomered in the third inning, his second of the season, to initially put Saint Mary's in front, 2-0.\nThe Gaels eight-game win streak over the Waves dating back to 2024 came to an end, but they'll look for the series win in the rubber match on Sunday.\nHOW IT HAPPENED\nSophomore southpaw\nTalin Gardini\nmade his first start of the season, after being used primarily as a bullpen arm for the Gaels, coming into Saturday's game with six appearances on the season. Gardini was in good form to start the year, and looked sharp again on Saturday, finishing his outing with five innings pitched and just one run allowed.\nThe Gaels got on the board first, thanks to a two-run homer from Griffith, his second of the season. Griffith scored Freschi on the play to give Saint Mary's a 2-0 lead in the third. Pepperdine would scrape one run across in the fifth before Gardini departed, but the Gaels still held a 2-1 lead going into the sixth.\nRedshirt junior\nNoah Waldeck\nwould start the sixth for the Gaels, and tossed some nice pitches but got unlucky with weak contact and bloop hits. A fielding error started the inning and, the Waves were able to plate the tying run two batters later on a 6-4-3 ground ball double play. Waldeck went on to induce a groundout to first to end the inning, with the game tied at two.\nPepperdine would make its move over the final three innings, where it combined to score seven runs over its final three at-bats, including a solo home-run in the ninth inning from Trey Dunn. The Gaels did not go quietly though, as they scored three runs over their final two at-bats, and even loaded the bases in the ninth, bringing the tying run to the plate in the form of\nBrayden Gutierrez\n. Gutierrez delivered a pinch-hit RBI single in the eighth, and would get one more crack at things in the ninth, but sent a 1-0 pitch to the warning track in right field, where it was caught for the final out. The Waves would hang on for the 9-5 victory to set up the rubber match on Sunday.\nGAME NOTES\nSaint Mary's got to ten hits in the ninth inning, marking the 18th time this season with double-digit hits.\nMakoa Sniffen\nled the Gaels with three hits for his ninth multi-hit game of the season.\nSniffen also had two doubles in the game, and now sits in second place on the team with seven.\nKashimoto pushed his hit streak to 15 games, going 2-for-2 with a run scored.\nDario Freschi\nmade his fourth start of the season in the DH spot for the Gaels and went 2-for-4 with two runs scored.\nGriffith connected on his second home run of the season and the fifth of his career.\nGardini made his first start on the mound this season and completed five innings, allowing just one run off of five hits.\nRedshirt freshman\nMax Johnson\nmade his first collegiate appearance on the mound for the Gaels.\nBrayden Gutierrez\nrecorded his second career hit and RBI, with his pinch-hit RBI single in the eighth inning.\nLOOKING AHEAD\nSunday's rubber match will take place at 1:00 PM at Luis Guisto Field at Br. Ronald Gallagher Stadium. Tickets can be bought online at smcgaels.com/tickets and you can catch all the action live on ESPN+.\nBe sure to follow your Gaels on Facebook, Instagram, and X to get all the latest Saint Mary's athletics updates and information.\n#GaelsRise",
